name: Stagecoach
text: Stagecoaches were designed to swap horses regularly for faster journeys.

name: Hancock Enterprise
text: Walter Hancock's steam buses were the first successful self-propelled road vehicles.

name: LGOC B-Type
text: The B-type was built in Walthamstow, London and gained electric lighting from 1912

name: AEC S-Type
text: The AEC S-type was an evolution of the K-type chassis which placed the driver alongside the engine for a shorter overall length.

name: Leyland Tiger TS
text: The Leyland Tiger coach featured a powerful 6-cylinder petrol engine.

name: AEC Regent I
text: The Tilling-bodied AEC Regent has a covered upper deck for passenger comfort in all weather.

name: Sentinel Steam Bus
text: Several buses were built on Sentinel steam lorry chassis.

name: Northern General SE6
text: The SE6 used a side-mounted engine to give more passenger space, and pioneered many features used in modern single-decker buses.

name: Dennis Ace
text: The Dennis Ace was a smaller bus based on a small lorry chassis.

name: Bristol L
text: The Bristol L was a single decker bus with art deco interior styling.

name: AEC Regent II
text: AEC restarted post-war bus production with the Regent II, a minor update of the Regent I chassis.

name: Bristol Lodekka
text: The Bristol Lodekka was designed for routes with low bridges, being shorter than a standard double-decker body.

name: Bristol LS
text: The Bristol LS was one of the first successful buses with an underfloor engine, and featured unitary construction rather than a separate body and chassis.

name: AEC Routemaster
text: The Routemaster is the quintessential London bus, with an long service life including use on dedicated heritage routes even after most were withdrawn.

name: BMMO CM5T
text: The "Midland Red" motorway services featured this turbocharged coach, capable of high speeds in the era before motorway speed limits.

name: Leyland Leopard
text: The Leyland Leopard was common throughout the UK, with some examples still in commercial use in the early 2000s.

name: Bedford VAL
text: The Bedford VAL had a distinguished film career, featuring prominently in The Italian Job with Harrington Legionnaire coachwork and in Magical Mystery Tour with a Plaxton Panorama body.

name: Leyland National
text: The Leyland National was designed to be simple and easy to service. Many operators extended the life of their Nationals by fitting newer engine models.

name: MCW Metrobus
text: The MCW Metrobus was built by Metro Cammell Weymann and saw use mainly in urban areas.

name: Volvo B10M
text: The Volvo B10M sold very well in the UK and was used widely by charter coach companies.

name: Leyland Olympian
text: The Olympian was the last bus to be manufactured under the Leyland name.

name: MCW Metrorider
text: The MCW Metrorider was a big improvement over van-based small buses. When MCW ended bus production in 1989 the rights to the design were bought by Optare, who continued making it until 2000.

name: Dennis Dart
text: The Dennis Dart was a small single decker bus produced with several body variants and a low-floor version called Dart SLF

name: Renault Agora
text: The Renault (later Irisbus) Agora is a low floor bus used across Europe, with 23 Optare-bodied models used for the Norwich park and ride service.

name: Dennis Trident 2
text: The Dennis Trident with Alexander ALX400 bodywork was used by a large variety of UK bus operators.

name: Optare Solo
text: The Solo, named for its low floor, is a unitary construction bus with an unsual front axle layout

name: Volvo B12M
text: The B12M is an updated version of the Volvo B10M

name: Mercedes-Benz Citaro
text: Although criticised for its length in inner cities and early problems with reliability, the Citaro "bendy bus" offers fast loading speeds on busy routes.

name: Dennis Enviro400
text: The Dennis Enviro400 is an updated version of the earlier Dennis Trident that is widely used across the UK for both city and rural services.

name: Wrightbus Pulsar (Hydrogen)
text: This unusual hydrogen-powered bus, based on a VDL SB200 chassis, was used in London for the RV1 tourist route

name: Wrightbus New Routemaster
text: Despite early teething problems with air conditioning and increased fare evasion due to the open rear platform, the "new bus for London" saw wide usage across the capital.

name: Optare Solo SR
text: The Solo SR is an updated version of the Solo with reduced weight and better fuel economy

name: Dennis Enviro400H MMC
text: The Dennis Enviro400H MMC has a hybrid system which improves acceleration away from a stop while reducing fuel use and emissions at the same time.

name: Horse-Drawn Dray
text: Drays were sturdy, low-sided wagons used for transporting heavy cargo. Some breweries still use horse-drawn drays to deliver beer locally.

name: Leyland Steam Van
text: The Leyland Steam van was the first vehicle produced by Leyland. It only offered a small advantage over its horse-drawn counterparts.

name: Foden 5 ton steam wagon
text: The Foden 5 ton wagon was an example of an "overtype" steam lorry in which the engine was mounted above the boiler.

name: Leyland X Type
text: The Leyland X Type used a large petrol engine for its motive power

name: Thornycroft Type J
text: The Thornycroft Type J was widely used in the First World War.

name: Scammell 7.5 Ton
text: The Scammell 7.5 ton had a low axle weight, allowing it to carry heavier loads than contemporary lorries.

name: Sentinel DG4
text: Steam lorries were popular into the 1930s due to their high power and speed compared to early internal combustion engines.

name: Beardmore Python
text: Beardmore was a taxi manufacturer that bought the rights to manufacture a French-designed tractor unit.

name: AEC Mammoth Major 8
text: The Mammoth was AEC's heaviest model and could carry large loads.

name: Leyland Badger
text: The Leyland Badger was typical of Leyland's petrol-powered trucks from the 1930s. They could be converted to 6x4 chassis to improve drivability on rough roads.

name: Scammell Scarab
text: The Scarab was traditionally used to transport goods and mail from stations to nearby towns.

name: Leyland Octopus
text: Eight wheeled "octopus" lorries could carry heavy loads while still keeping relatively low axle weights to reduce road damage.

name: Foden S20
text: The S20's cab used a traditional construction of both wood and metal, despite the streamlined appearance.

name: Bedford TK
text: The Bedford TK was a versatile small lorry that was adapted to many derivatives, including a telephone pole installation vehicle and the four-wheel-drive military Bedford MK

name: Thompson Autotanker
text: The futuristic Autotanker used a rear-engined Leyland Dromedary chassis, built for the prototype. Unfortunately the real vehicle was not used commercially, although thousands of Matchbox toy versions were produced.

name: Foden S21
text: The Foden S21 featured a futuristic cab design and a two-stroke diesel engine.

name: Guy Big J4T
text: Designed for motorway operation, the Guy Big J featured a high-revving Cummins engine. This is the articulated version.

name: Guy Big J6
text: Designed for motorway operation, the Guy Big J featured a high-revving Cummins engine. This is the rigid version.

name: Leyland Beaver
text: The Leyland Beaver was one of many trucks fitted with the "Ergomatic" cab design, designed for efficient use of space and driver comfort.

name: Ford D Series
text: The Ford D Series was built to compete with the Bedford TK and introduced a new range of diesel engines

name: Saviem SM
text: The Saviem SM Europe was the result of a collaboration between Saviem and MAN, where Saviem supplied cabs and MAN provided engines. Although more common in France a few were used in the UK.

name: AEC Mandator V8
text: The AEC Mandator V8 had a powerful engine for its day, and drivers would often claim high speeds even with a fully loaded lorry.

name: Volvo F10
text: The Volvo F10 spearheaded a wave of powerful European trucks arriving in the UK.

name: Leyland T45
text: The Leyland T45 was an attempt to revitalise the commercial vehicles offering of British Leyland. It was a common sight in the '80s and early '90s.

name: Ford Cargo
text: The Ford Cargo featured styling details from Ford's early 1980s car range.

name: ERF C-Series
text: The ERF C-series introduced an improved cab design and several chassis improvements.

name: Mercedes LK
text: The Mercedes LK featured angular lines and a tilting cab.

name: ERF E-Series
text: The E-series sold widely in the UK, and Cummins-engined models had a distinctive exhaust note.

name: Scania 3 Series
text: The Scania 3 series has an excellent reputation for reliability and was well-regarded in its era.

name: Iveco Eurocargo
text: The Iveco Eurocargo is a medium duty lorry useful for routes with lower cargo demands.

name: Scania 4 Series
text: The Scania 4 series modernised the 3 series design, and could be configured with powerful V8 engines.

name: Foden Alpha
text: The Alpha was the last truck to bear the Foden nameplate.

name: Renault Magnum
text: The Renault Magnum has aerodynamic design ideas from Renault prototypes to reduce fuel consumption.

name: DAF LF
text: The DAF LF is a development of the earlier Leyland Roadrunner, and is available with many powertrain options including a hybrid.

name: Scania R Series
text: The Scania R series continues Scania's truck line, with the option of powerful V8s.

name: Mitsubishi Fuso Canter
text: Although earlier generations were not commonly seen in the UK, the 2004 model has been popular with many firms.

name: Volvo FM9
text: The Volvo FM range is part of Volvo's strategy to build a global family of trucks.

name: Ford Model T
text: The Ford Model T was produced in many forms over its long life, with delivery vans being a common option.

name: Austin 10hp
text: The Austin 10hp was a van derived from the car of the same name.

name: Ford Thames 400E
text: The Ford Thames was designed to bring Ford's van offering up to the standards of its more modern competitors.

name: Commer FC
text: The Commer FC is a classic British van. The forward-control layout and hard to reach engine made it harder to maintain than more conventional vans such as Ford's Transit.

name: Ford Transit Mk1
text: The Transit was a huge leap on from the narrow-tracked delivery vans it replaced, with a stable chassis and performance suitable for the expanding network of motorways.

name: Ford Transit Mk3
text: The Mk3 Transit introduced a new aerodynamic body shell to the model.

name: Bedford Rascal
text: The Bedford Rascal (also Suzuki Carry) was a tiny van for economical local deliveries, with a 970cc engine.

name: Mercedes-Benz Sprinter
text: The Sprinter is famed in the van world for its powerful engine options and high top speed.

name: Ford Transit Custom
text: The Transit Custom continues the long Transit line with a modern van.

name: Austin FX4
text: The Austin FX4 is the definitive London taxi, with modern models still imitating its classic shape.

name: Leyland Sherpa
text: The Leyland Sherpa saw use across the UK with many government agencies. It also had a cameo in the James Bond film 'The Spy Who Loved Me', being torn apart by Jaws

name: Ford Cortina
text: The Cortina consistently topped best selling lists throughout its life. The squared-off Mk4 was introduced in 1976.

name: Ford Transit Mk3 Minibus
text: The Mk3 Transit introduced a new aerodynamic body shell to the model. It was often sold in minibus form.

name: Vauxhall Omega
text: The Vauxhall Omega was the last of the large rear-wheel-drive saloons from a mainstream manufacturer, with higher specification models featuring a V6 petrol engine.

name: LTI TX1
text: The TX1 was the first truly successful attempt to replace the venerable Austin FX4.

name: Volvo S40 T5
text: The Volvo S40 T5 featured the same five-cylinder engine as the Focus ST in a comfortable saloon car.

name: Toyota Prius
text: The hybrid Prius can operate on battery power alone at lower speeds, making it a popular minicab in tows and cities.

name: Renault Trafic Minibus
text: The Renault Trafic is popular as a minibus, and is used for everything from schools to ski transfers.

name: BMW 335d Touring
text: The 335d Touring offers more than 300bhp from a 3-litre twin turbo diesel engine, giving 0-60 in under five seconds.

name: Horse-Drawn Tram
text: With the low friction of steel rails, horses could draw many more passengers on level ground when attached to a tram.

name: Grantham's Steam Tram
text: John Grantham's steam tramcar was an early attempt to replace horse-drawn trams.

name: Conduit Car
text: Conduit trams drew their power from a conduit running in the ground. This system was widely used on early London tramways.

name: GF Milne Tram
text: The GF Milne "Car No. 1" holds the Guinness World Record for oldest tram still operating on its original line.

name: MER Tunnel Car
text: The Tunnel Cars were named after their long interiors, originally fitted with longitudinal seating.

name: Fleetwood Box Car
text: Fleetwood box cars operated between Blackpool and Fleetwood in the early 20th century.

name: MER Winter Saloon
text: Despite the name, enclosed winter saloon trams were often operated year-round.

name: Marton Box Car
text: The Marton box cars, named for their sharp edges, had narrow entrances and were unpopular with passengers.

name: UEC Blackpool "Toastrack"
text: Toastrack trams were very popular with tourists during summer months.

name: Standard Car
text: Standard trams were an attempt to replace the many different varieties of tram operating on Blackpool's tramways with a standardised model.

name: English Electric Balloon
text: The "Balloon" tram was so named due to its bulbous streamlined shape.

name: Coronation Tram
text: Although technically advanced, the Coronation tram had high power requirements and poor reliability.

name: Progress Twin Car
text: The Progress Twin Cars were rebuilt from earlier Blackpool trams.

name: Jubilee Tram
text: The Jubilee trams were extended and rebodied Balloon trams.

name: Centenary Tram
text: Centenary trams used large numbers of bus parts.

name: LHB P86 Stock
text: The P86 stock was used both on London's DLR system as a light rail vehicle and in the German city of Essen as a tram.

name: Bombardier CR4000
text: The CR4000 was the first tram to run in London since the end of the original system in 1952.

name: Bombardier B07 Stock
text: B07 stock was the first type to operate as a 3-car train on London's DLR.

name: Flexity 2
text: The Flexity 2 is a modern low-floor tram with a large capacity and multiple doors for fast loading.

name: Vossloh Class 399
text: The Vossloh Class 399 is a powerful and advanced tram/train hybrid vehicle.

name: Horse-Drawn Wagons
text: Horse drawn cargo tramway systems were the precursor to modern railways.

name: Y6 0-4-0
text: The Y6 steam tram was designed for running on public roads.

name: J70 0-6-0
text: The J70 steam tram was a more powerful version of the Y6 designed to handle more cargo.

name: Y10 "Super Sentinel"
text: This Sentinel tram engine had two engines and a two-speed gearbox.

name: FC Hibberd Planet
text: FC Hibberd built many different types of locomotive under the "Planet" nameplate, often using a Dorman engine.

name: Drewry Shunter
text: Diesel shunters with special tramway adaptations were used to replace steam trams in East Anglia.
